commit.message:
yarn upgrade

there are a huge amount of warnings from yarn, so at some point all of that should probably be looked at

also, do i really need 2 yarn files, one in `protocol` and one in the main directory?

add escape clause for spurious events

truffle is emitting these for some reason. we need to figure out why. in the mean time, we can easily just work around it by adding this return statement.
a few additional small readme changes

Merge pull request #7 from JohnSt99/patch-1

improved intuitiveness & added example code

some additional touchups and code style things

i guess we are adding semicolons in the README now.

final docs update

mirrored at https://eprint.iacr.org/2020/293

fix bug: register the "empty" account

actually, it's interesting. even with no "beneficiary" argument supplied, the [0x00, 0x00] account will be credited, and this can (probably) be spent from using a secret key of 0. so in this way miners could make "raking" transactions. probably'd be better to have a special "rake" method in the contract, so that the extra gas doesn't have to be spent.

or maybe it's better this way, so that the miner's identity can be kept private... intriguing.

various fees fixes

updated the truffle test to dynamically retrieve the fee. made the "beneficiary" argument optional (especially useful in case fee is 0). in this case it will burn the fees to the empty account.

merge branch for "transaction fees" (#2)

now, we have an intrinsic mechanism for transaction fees. a sender can specify a "beneficiary" who will receive the fixed fee. In practice, this could be a "miner", who will then mine the transaction voluntarily, even though it (say) offers no gas.

refactors. only define fee once...

...in the contract. then pull it in and use it elsewhere. various other improvements.
some refactors and improvements in client

client-side FFT optimizations.

only compute the array of roots of unity once. pass it into subcalls. only FFT the base vector once; use the FFT in both hadamards / convolutions. significantly improves the prover time.

more contract optimizations

in the FFT and the recursive polynomial evaluation calculation.

significant optimizations of contracts

avoiding using exp() and inv(). various improvements. save a couple hundred thousand gas per zether verification, at least. a few million for larger anonsets.

modernization for contracts and testing

upgrade all contracts to Solidity 0.7.0. now use Truffle and Ganache for a proper testing and deployment infrastructure. got rid of the old tests. This should be a better experience for everyone.

huge refactor. improved efficiency

...of the prover by at least a few-hundred milliseconds. code should also now be clearer and more concise.
another round of maintenance: docs + yarn

adopt Esgin et al.'s optimization

see \S 1.3 of https://eprint.iacr.org/2019/1287.pdf. the pairs (A, B), (C, D), and (E, F) can be combined into a single pair. reduces proof size by a few hundred bytes. thanks to them!

improve some error messages

also improve behavior upon failure of registration: account remains un-set, so that error message triggers in fund / burn methods.

small refactor: remove bTransfer from burn proof

isn't used at all in proving and verifying, and doesn't need to be part of the statement hash / salt.

improved version of Sigma-Bullets

the latest ePrint version of the Zether paper (https://eprint.iacr.org/2019/191.pdf) actually features a better Sigma-Bullets protocol, which is correct and secure (i.e., cf. the old version https://crypto.stanford.edu/~buenz/papers/zether.pdf). It's also slighly more efficient and elegant than our version. Thus we've adopted the new version, and also adjusted both the implementation and the technical report accordingly. thanks to them for their work. in particular, we _no longer_ use a variant derived from bbuenz / BulletProofLib (which was correct but not secure, and which we had to amend).

refactor: ZSC uses Utils

and all points are of type G1Point, isntead of being "emulated" as bytes32[2]'s.

the advantage of this is essentially that the ZSC can use the "heavy" tools for scalar and point manipulation, and doesn't have to rely on inline assembly. there are a few things that Solidity doesn't properly support yet, so we've had to work around those. but it's an improvement.

security update: registration

now everyone must first demonstrate possession of his _own_ secret key (i.e., by publishing a signature) before participating. this is to prevent a "rogue key" insider attack on multi-recipient El Gamal, see Bellare, Boldyreva and Staddon 2003. In short, an attacker could have generated a "false key" derived from an honest one, and (if he can trick other users into including both him and said honest account in an anonset together) could have used the false key to decrypt the balance change in the honest key. this is thwarted if we just ensure that people know their _own_ secret key.

also, docs now feature _full_ security proofs.

Merge pull request #23 from ibudisteanu/patch-1

package name is `bn.js`. Node.js on Linux it is case sensitive

package name is `bn.js`. Node.js on Linux it is case sensitive

The packages `bn.js` is lowercase and node.js on Linux is case sensitive. Probably you have either another package called BN.js which is uppercase or you got a link with BN.js in the node_modules

refactor: IP verifier own contract

and deployments are now cheap enough for mainnet use.

the most significant change is that the "g, h, gs, and hs" parameters are now hard-coded into the contract code, which cuts down on storage costs. in particular, each individual deployment can be carried out for 4-6 million gas. this recourse was suggested in the original zether paper, and also by @ibudisteanu (thanks to them).

additionally, the inner product verifier is now a separate contract, used by both the ZetherVerifier and BurnVerifier contracts. this cuts down on repeated code and is more elegant.

version bump for BN.js

updates as per fix of https://github.com/indutny/elliptic/issues/191. also a few other adjustments. thanks @ibudisteanu for noticing a naming inconsistency.

more shuffling and renaming.

also, now use different randomnesses for \bar g and \bar D. finally, substantial updates to the docs.

infrastructure docs updates.

minor typos and improvements

maintenance update for truffle

bumped a number of versions (now use mainline web3 1.x). significantly expanded the truffle tests. also now change web3.transactionConfirmationBlocks _within_ the Client object (less error-prone).

now featuring logarithmically-sized proofs.

proof _size_ now grows logarithmically in the size of the anonset. i also have security proof sketches in this new setting, which are significantly more involved. please see docs/AnonZether.pdf for a precise specification of the new protocol, as well as for the proofs. these are only sketches at this point, and are liable to change.

more adjustments: separate randomnesses

for each i, j (instead of just for each i), also separate randomness pi for (C_Ln, C_Rn). It is a bit difficult to show that this is _strictly necessary_ for zero-knowledge, but it makes the proofs go through more naturally, and doesn't affect performance much (just have to generate a few extra random scalars). Thus probably the right thing to do. open question to make this exact.

also: the docs now feature (sketches of) security proofs!

security update: zero knowledge

mitigates an "insider attack" on zero knowledge, whereby a member of the anonset could have determined the sender _or_ receiver (depending on his position). in brief: some member y_k could have computed \bar{g}^{sk_k}, and compared the resulting quantity to each \bar{y_j,i}. the result would have revealed the value of idx_j (for one value j). a similar procedure could have been done against \bar{D} and \bar{C_j,i}.

the issue was essentially that randomness was being re-used across re-encryptions for each value i. now fixed.

a number of security updates and refactors

made a number of substantial changes to the protocol, mainly to the effect of making "sigma bullets" more secure. the protocol, previously, was not sound as written (for reasons separate from my prior zero knowledge fix). this re-orders a number of things, and changes the reduction from ElGamal to Bulleproofs.

the main issue can be briefly described as follows: there was no proof that the _message_ of (C, D) was well-formed, i.e. an exponent of g alone. If the prover put an _arbitrary_ Pedersen commitment in the message (i.e., with an "h" part) the prover could have still succeeded, breaking his account and the recipient's.

in addition, we now conduct our one-out-of-many proofs "first". this is important for witness extraction (in the security proofs, forthcoming). finally, we made substantial changes to the docs.

a number of docs updates...

which reflect the adjustments to the protocol made in recent commits.

adjust variable names to match docs

though the diff is unfortunately large, this will make things much easier in the future for people who want to cross-reference the two.

now use rho = r * sigma, pi = r' * sigma

this choice is more parsimonious, and slightly more efficient, for the prover; it also avoids an edge case in which w = sigma and r-bar required division by 0. it should still have zero knowledge. details will be described in the docs.

small README update

registration doesn't exist anymore... adjust the mock printout accordingly.

eliminate division by challenge w

though this is only _theoretically_ relevant in the exceptional case that w == 0 (negligibly probable under Fiat--Shamir), we can get some concrete gains in efficiency (and elegance!) if we never divide by w. details will be forthcoming in the docs.

fix zero-knowledge vulnerability

This commit mitigates a serious zero-knowledge vulnerability in basic Zether (Sigma-Bullets), which could have allowed an observer to determine b' and b* using only 2^64 work (and far less in some cases). The full amended protocol is implemented in this commit; it's also specified in AnonZether.pdf (the attack and its fix are described on page 6).

various fixes

docs, plus BN.js capitalization, plus EC stuff (upgrade to 6.5.1 relase)

eliminate registration

As far as mitigating the "front-running" issues goes, a simpler, more elegant and equally secure alternative to account pre-registration is the "Schnorr signature" approach, where the generic Burn proof is converted to one which _in addition_ serves to sign `msg.sender`. Indeed, if we just include `msg.sender` in the list of things which get hashed to produce the sigma protocol challenge, the effect is that the proof simultaneously signs it. In particular, if `msg.sender` changes, the proof will become invalid, and further can't be modified to suit the new value without access to the private key. Thanks to Benedikt Bünz for suggesting this approach.

some maintenance

running `yarn upgrade` switches certain things to web3 1.2.1, which breaks things?

IBFT support

... with `--istanbul.blockperiod 1`. Everything works; I have had to bump up epoch length by a couple of seconds, because of the increased block time. This has more of a (relative) impact for smaller anonsets, of course. However it seems that the more sophisticated consensus protocol is worth the wait.

truffle fixes!

migrate and test should now be working for both develop and "quorum" networks.

better IBFT explanation in README

Update to give a better explanation for why the code as currently written only supports Raft.

update Node version in README

Node v12 is necessary in order to properly execute `.flat()`, i.e. https://github.com/jpmorganchase/anonymous-zether/blob/d228d63cf53a7369602b4f4c87b354e7cc94d41b/packages/anonymous.js/src/prover/zether/anon.js#L86.

readme update

mention that IBFT is not supported.

the reason for this is actually quite silly: Raft reports `block.timestamp` in nanoseconds, as opposed to milliseconds. As a consequence, we have to divide by 1000000 at https://github.com/jpmorganchase/anonymous-zether/blob/3621c933ea500320da3dae7e970ff01abe22ca6d/packages/protocol/contracts/ZSC.sol#L66 and https://github.com/jpmorganchase/anonymous-zether/blob/3621c933ea500320da3dae7e970ff01abe22ca6d/packages/anonymous.js/src/client.js#L37; on the other hand, this makes it incompatible with regular Ethereum and with IBFT. In the future, Raft should be updated to use the standard semantics.

minor refactor: move "initialize" to top level

didn't make sense as a method of the account object alone (it modifies the class-wide _epochLength attribute).

remove async declaration from initialize

since the function returns a promise anyway, it seems like this is unnecessary / a "no-op".

also, a few adjustments to the readme

even further FFT optimizations

for elegance as much as performance... if i conduct my circular shifts in the opposite direction (arbitrary which one), then a few "flip"s become unnecessary later, and the convolution is more natural. also, see AnonZether.pdf for updated performance measurements, encompassing this commit and the last.

FFT even-indexed outputs optimization

because I only use circular shifts of _even_ order, i only require the even-indexed values of the result of circular convolution. thus i can use this optimization https://dsp.stackexchange.com/a/30699 on the inverse transform (instead of just tossing the odd values). this leads to modest but pretty substantial improvements in all measurements of runtime, especially for larger anonsets

merge in branch: re-rewrite prover in Javascript.

see PR for details. merges in a significant refactor in which the whole prover is re-written in Javascript.

new web3 dependency magically appeared?

probably a good idea to fill out  with a more complete list.

bump epoch estimation...

this is tricky. javascript is slightly slower than Java, which is causing me to miss epochs.

everything working?

more bugs fixed involving unserialization.

transfer proofs work

i blame https://www.wsj.com/graphics/apple-still-hasnt-fixed-its-macbook-keyboard-problem/ for some of them

addressed some subtle bugs...

essentially, i need to transpose the bytes32[2][][2]s into bytes32[2][2][]s, because _the latter_ are what Solidity accepts.

burns working

mention that IBFT is not supported.

the reason for this is actually quite silly: Raft reports `block.timestamp` in nanoseconds, as opposed to milliseconds. As a consequence, we have to divide by 1000000 at https://github.com/jpmorganchase/anonymous-zether/blob/3621c933ea500320da3dae7e970ff01abe22ca6d/packages/protocol/contracts/ZSC.sol#L66 and https://github.com/jpmorganchase/anonymous-zether/blob/3621c933ea500320da3dae7e970ff01abe22ca6d/packages/anonymous.js/src/client.js#L37; on the other hand, this makes it incompatible with regular Ethereum and with IBFT. for elegance as much as performance... if i conduct my circular shifts in the opposite direction (arbitrary which one), then a few "flip"s become unnecessary later, and the convolution is more natural. also, see AnonZether.pdf for updated performance measurements, encompassing this commit and the last.
FFT even-indexed outputs optimization

because I only use circular shifts of _even_ order, i only require the even-indexed values of the result of circular convolution. thus i can use this optimization https://dsp.stackexchange.com/a/30699 on the inverse transform (instead of just tossing the odd values). this leads to modest but pretty substantial improvements in all measurements of runtime, especially for larger anonsets
